' ============================================================================
' usage example
' ============================================================================

note as UsageExample
  **usage example**

  {
    // create input manager
    InputOutputManager inputManager =
        new InputOutputManager();
    inputManager.init();

    // configure input mapping
    InputMapping mapping = inputManager.getInputMapping();
    mapping.bindKey(Input.Keys.W, MOVE_UP);
    mapping.bindKey(Input.Keys.S, MOVE_DOWN);
    mapping.bindKey(Input.Keys.A, MOVE_LEFT);
    mapping.bindKey(Input.Keys.D, MOVE_RIGHT);
    mapping.bindKey(Input.Keys.SPACE, JUMP);

    // game loop
    while (running) {
      float deltaTime = getDeltaTime();

      // update input state
      inputManager.update(deltaTime);

      // query inputs
      IInputQuery input = inputManager;

      // continuous actions (movement)
      if (input.isActionActive(MOVE_UP)) {
        player.moveUp(deltaTime);
      }

      // single-shot actions (jump)
      if (input.getActionState(JUMP) == PRESSED) {
        player.jump();
      }
    }

    // cleanup
    inputManager.shutdown();
  }

  **rebinding example**

  {
    // allow user to rebind controls
    void rebindControl(ActionId action) {
      System.out.println("press key for " + action);

      int keyCode = waitForKeyPress();

      InputMapping mapping =
          inputManager.getInputMapping();
      mapping.bindKey(keyCode, action);

      System.out.println("bound " + action +
                        " to key " + keyCode);
    }
  }
end note

' ============================================================================
' state update algorithm
' ============================================================================

note as StateUpdateAlgorithm
  **state update algorithm**

  {
    protected void onUpdate(float deltaTime) {
      ObjectSet<ActionId> actions = getBoundActions();

      for (ActionId action : actions) {
        boolean currentlyDown = isPhysicallyDown(action);
        Boolean wasDown = previousDown.get(action);

        InputState newState;

        if (currentlyDown && !wasDown) {
          newState = InputState.PRESSED;
        } else if (currentlyDown && wasDown) {
          newState = InputState.HELD;
        } else if (!currentlyDown && wasDown) {
          newState = InputState.RELEASED;
        } else {
          // not pressed, don't track
          actionStates.remove(action);
          previousDown.remove(action);
          continue;
        }

        actionStates.put(action, newState);
        previousDown.put(action, currentlyDown);
      }
    }
  }

  characteristics:
  - frame-based state detection
  - only tracks bound actions
  - removes inactive actions
end note

' ============================================================================
' design patterns summary
' ============================================================================

note as DesignPatterns
  **design patterns in input system**

  1. **strategy pattern**
     - InputMapping as strategy
     - rebindable control schemes
     - runtime configuration

  2. **state pattern variant**
     - InputState enum
     - PRESSED → HELD → RELEASED
     - frame-based state tracking

  3. **value object pattern**
     - ActionId as immutable value
     - proper equals/hashCode
     - type-safe identifiers

  4. **null object pattern**
     - ActionId.NONE for unbound inputs
     - avoids null checks

  5. **facade pattern**
     - InputOutputManager as facade
     - hides libgdx input polling
     - simple query interface

  benefits:
  - rebindable controls
  - decoupled input logic
  - testable with mocks
  - frame-accurate state tracking
  - type-safe action identifiers
end note

@enduml
